│ stop({"edit_points": [[1436, 1442,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp"]], "thoughts":  │
│ "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe miscompilation arises after loop            │
│ vectorization: a conditional body (executed only when iv==10) is widened to   │
│ operate on two lanes (iv=9 and iv=10). In the vector IR, the division in lane │
│ 0 is correctly predicated and replaced by a poison value via a predicated PHI │
│ (%3). However, subsequent address calculations (add/shl/sub/gep) and,         │
│ critically, the wide load use this poison operand for the inactive lane. The  │
│ widened load is emitted unmasked (wide.load). In LLVM IR semantics, loading   │
│ from a poison pointer operand is immediate UB, regardless of memory safety.   │
│ The original scalar loop never executed those instructions for iv=9. Thus the │
│ transformation makes the program less defined: the source is defined, target  │
│ triggers UB. Alive2 confirms this: target performs a wide load with a poison  │
│ pointer lane.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe produced vector IR shows:\n  %3 │
│ = phi i16 [ poison, %vector.body ], [ %2, %pred.sdiv.if ]\n  ...\n  %7 = shl  │
│ i16 %3, 14\n  %8 = sub i16 %6, %7\n  %9 = getelementptr i64, ptr @src, i16    │
│ %8\n  ...\n  %wide.load = load <2 x i64>, ptr %10, align 1\nThe load is       │
│ unconditional and unmasked. Only the stores are predicated. No mask guards    │
│ the load, so lane 0's poison-derived pointer is dereferenced. The             │
│ legality/cost model decided no mask was required for this load                │
│ (Legal->isMaskRequired(load)==false) and treated it as safe to speculate. The │
│ first transformation (adding canonical IV) is not itself the cause; the issue │
│ is in the decision logic for masking/predication of loads when their pointer  │
│ operand is produced in a predicated block from potentially poison             │
│ values.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nFunction blockCanBePredicated             │
│ (LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp) determines which instructions in predicated   │
│ blocks require masking. For loads it currently inserts them into MaskedOp     │
│ only if their pointer operand is not found in SafePtrs:\n  if (auto *LI =     │
│ dyn_cast<LoadInst>(&I)) {\n    if                                             │
│ (!SafePtrs.count(LI->getPointerOperand()))\n      MaskedOp.insert(LI);\n      │
│ continue;\n  }\nSafePtrs collects pointer operands considered dereferenceable │
│ (fault-safe) either because they appear in non-predicated blocks or proved    │
│ dereferenceable via SCEV/dereferenceability queries. This reasoning ignores   │
│ the possibility that, after vectorization and predicate widening, operands    │
│ feeding the pointer become poison for inactive lanes. Speculation safety in   │
│ LLVM must also preserve definedness w.r.t poison; using a poison pointer      │
│ operand in an active (unmasked) load is UB. Because the pointer operand (a    │
│ GEP) is created inside the predicated block, and its indices may become       │
│ poison when the defining operations are predicated, marking the load as       │
│ \"safe\" (no mask required) is incorrect. We must conservatively require      │
│ masking (or later scalarization) for loads in predicated blocks whose pointer │
│ operand is not loop invariant, even if the base pointer is                    │
│ dereferenceable.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 1436-1442 in       │
│ LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp inside blockCanBePredicated to strengthen the   │
│ condition for marking a load as requiring masking. We add logic: if the load  │
│ is in a block that needs predication and its pointer operand is defined       │
│ within that block (thus can carry poison when vectorized) or is not loop      │
│ invariant, force MaskedOp insertion. This prevents generation of an unmasked  │
│ wide load consuming poison.\nReplacement snippet conceptually:\n  if (auto    │
│ *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(&I)) {\n    Value *PtrOp =                           │
│ LI->getPointerOperand();\n    bool PtrDefinedInPredicatedBB =                 │
│ isa<Instruction>(PtrOp) && cast<Instruction>(PtrOp)->getParent() == BB;\n     │
│ bool PtrNotLoopInvariant = !TheLoop->isLoopInvariant(PtrOp);\n    if          │
│ (!SafePtrs.count(PtrOp) || (blockNeedsPredication(BB) &&                      │
│ (PtrDefinedInPredicatedBB || PtrNotLoopInvariant)))\n                         │
│ MaskedOp.insert(LI);\n    continue;\n  }\nThis ensures Legal->isMaskRequired  │
│ returns true for such loads, causing vectorization to emit a masked load (or  │
│ scalarize), preventing UB from poison pointer lanes.\n\nRationale: We avoid   │
│ deeper poison tracking and use a conservative syntactic check that captures   │
│ the problematic case. Pointer defined inside the predicated block and not     │
│ loop invariant implies its computation can be suppressed for some lanes,      │
│ creating poison. Masking allows inactive lanes' pointer values to be ignored  │
│ safely.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy tightening the load masking condition in        │
│ blockCanBePredicated, loads whose pointer operands may become poison after    │
