│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The miscompilation arises after loop vectorization: a conditional body        │
│ (executed only when iv==10) is widened to operate on two lanes (iv=9 and      │
│ iv=10). In the vector IR, the division in lane 0 is correctly predicated and  │
│ replaced by a poison value via a predicated PHI (%3). However, subsequent     │
│ address calculations (add/shl/sub/gep) and, critically, the wide load use     │
│ this poison operand for the inactive lane. The widened load is emitted        │
│ unmasked (wide.load). In LLVM IR semantics, loading from a poison pointer     │
│ operand is immediate UB, regardless of memory safety. The original scalar     │
│ loop never executed those instructions for iv=9. Thus the transformation      │
│ makes the program less defined: the source is defined, target triggers UB.    │
│ Alive2 confirms this: target performs a wide load with a poison pointer lane. │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The produced vector IR shows:                                                 │
│   %3 = phi i16 [ poison, %vector.body ], [ %2, %pred.sdiv.if ]                │
│   ...                                                                         │
│   %7 = shl i16 %3, 14                                                         │
│   %8 = sub i16 %6, %7                                                         │
│   %9 = getelementptr i64, ptr @src, i16 %8                                    │
│   ...                                                                         │
│   %wide.load = load <2 x i64>, ptr %10, align 1                               │
│ The load is unconditional and unmasked. Only the stores are predicated. No    │
│ mask guards the load, so lane 0's poison-derived pointer is dereferenced. The │
│ legality/cost model decided no mask was required for this load                │
│ (Legal->isMaskRequired(load)==false) and treated it as safe to speculate. The │
│ first transformation (adding canonical IV) is not itself the cause; the issue │
│ is in the decision logic for masking/predication of loads when their pointer  │
│ operand is produced in a predicated block from potentially poison values.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Function blockCanBePredicated (LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp) determines      │
│ which instructions in predicated blocks require masking. For loads it         │
│ currently inserts them into MaskedOp only if their pointer operand is not     │
│ found in SafePtrs:                                                            │
│   if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(&I)) {                                    │
│     if (!SafePtrs.count(LI->getPointerOperand()))                             │
│       MaskedOp.insert(LI);                                                    │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│   }                                                                           │
│ SafePtrs collects pointer operands considered dereferenceable (fault-safe)    │
│ either because they appear in non-predicated blocks or proved dereferenceable │
│ via SCEV/dereferenceability queries. This reasoning ignores the possibility   │
│ that, after vectorization and predicate widening, operands feeding the        │
│ pointer become poison for inactive lanes. Speculation safety in LLVM must     │
│ also preserve definedness w.r.t poison; using a poison pointer operand in an  │
│ active (unmasked) load is UB. Because the pointer operand (a GEP) is created  │
│ inside the predicated block, and its indices may become poison when the       │
│ defining operations are predicated, marking the load as "safe" (no mask       │
│ required) is incorrect. We must conservatively require masking (or later      │
│ scalarization) for loads in predicated blocks whose pointer operand is not    │
│ loop invariant, even if the base pointer is dereferenceable.                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 1436-1442 in LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp inside                  │
│ blockCanBePredicated to strengthen the condition for marking a load as        │
│ requiring masking. We add logic: if the load is in a block that needs         │
│ predication and its pointer operand is defined within that block (thus can    │
│ carry poison when vectorized) or is not loop invariant, force MaskedOp        │
│ insertion. This prevents generation of an unmasked wide load consuming        │
│ poison.                                                                       │
│ Replacement snippet conceptually:                                             │
│   if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(&I)) {                                    │
│     Value *PtrOp = LI->getPointerOperand();                                   │
│     bool PtrDefinedInPredicatedBB = isa<Instruction>(PtrOp) &&                │
│ cast<Instruction>(PtrOp)->getParent() == BB;                                  │
│     bool PtrNotLoopInvariant = !TheLoop->isLoopInvariant(PtrOp);              │
│     if (!SafePtrs.count(PtrOp) || (blockNeedsPredication(BB) &&               │
│ (PtrDefinedInPredicatedBB || PtrNotLoopInvariant)))                           │
│       MaskedOp.insert(LI);                                                    │
│     continue;                                                                 │
│   }                                                                           │
│ This ensures Legal->isMaskRequired returns true for such loads, causing       │
│ vectorization to emit a masked load (or scalarize), preventing UB from poison │
│ pointer lanes.                                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: We avoid deeper poison tracking and use a conservative syntactic   │
│ check that captures the problematic case. Pointer defined inside the          │
│ predicated block and not loop invariant implies its computation can be        │
│ suppressed for some lanes, creating poison. Masking allows inactive lanes'    │
│ pointer values to be ignored safely.                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By tightening the load masking condition in blockCanBePredicated, loads whose │
│ pointer operands may become poison after predication will be masked. The      │
│ vectorizer will no longer emit an unconditional wide load with a poison       │
│ pointer operand, preserving defined behavior and eliminating the              │
│ miscompilation. This conservative change only affects predicated blocks, and  │
│ safe invariant loads remain unmasked.                                         │
│                                                                               │
